#: {{synonyms|en|glade}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ferdinand von Wrangell [''i.e.'', {{w|Ferdinand von Wrangel}}]|chapter=V|editor={{w|Edward Sabine}}|title=Narrative of an Expedition to the Polar Sea, in the Years 1820, 1821, 1822 & 1823.{{nb...|Commanded by Lieutenant, now Admiral Ferdinand von Wrangell, of the Russian Imperial Navy.}}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=James Madden and Co.,{{nb...|8, Leadenhall Street.}}|year=1844|pages=102–103|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=m-MDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA103|oclc=317512813|passage=We immediately ascended a hill, and saw that the supposed land was nothing but hummocks of ice, piled up beyond a large '''Polynia''', or space of open water, which extended from east to west, as far as the eye could reach.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=The Expedition in Search of Sir {{w|John Franklin}}. [From the ''New York Tribune''.]|editor=[[w:Eliakim Littell|E[liakim] Littell]]|magazine=Littel’s Living Age|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=Published by E. Littel & Company; Philadelphia, Pa.: Getz & Buck,{{nb...|3 Hart’s Building.}}; New York, N.Y.: Dewitt & Davenport,{{nb...|Tribune Buildings.}}|date=8 November 1851|volume=XXXI|issue=CCCXC|section=chapter XXII|page=242|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=pD0UjrjEziAC&pg=PA242|column=1|oclc=913200987|passage=The American Expedition, therefore, was in a position more favourable to the search. It was in a far higher latitude, and the so-called '''''polyna''''' (open sea) could not have been far distant, but the inevitable drift into the waters of Lancaster Sound was fatal to its spring progress, and fatal to the chances which the enterprise had won.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=E[lisha] K[ent] Kane|authorlink=Elisha Kent Kane|title=Paper on ‘Access to an Open Polar Sea along a North American Meridian.’|journal=[[w:Geographical Review|Bulletin of the American Geographical and Statistical Society]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Published for the [[w:American Geographical Society|[American Geographical and Statistical] Society]] by [[w:George Palmer Putnam|G[eorge] P[almer] Putnam]],{{nb...|10 Park Place.}}|month=January|year=1853|volume=I|issue=2|page=87|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_eufAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA87|oclc=758332107|passage=The Circum-Polar ice, as I will venture to name it, may be said to bound an imperfect circle of 6000 miles in circumference, {{...}} But theory has determined that this great surface is not continuous. It is an annulus, a ring surrounding an area of open water,—the '''Polynya''', or Iceless Sea. '''Polynya''' is a Russian word, signifying an open space; and it is used by the Siberians to indicate the occasional vacancies which occur in a frozen water surface.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=The Polar Seas and Sir {{w|John Franklin}}|magazine=[[w:Putnam's Magazine|Putnam’s Monthly. A Magazine of Literature, Science, and Art]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:G. P. Putnam's Sons|G[eorge] P[almer] Putnam & Co.]],{{nb...|10 Park Place.}}; London: [[w:Sampson Low|Sampson Low, Son & Co.]]|month=June|year=1853|volume=I|issue=VI|page=635|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ICE0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA635|column=2|oclc=221113463|passage=Hoping to reach the starting-place in the early season of navigation, he &#91;{{w|Elisha Kent Kane}}&#93; intends to follow his course of travel nearly upon a meridional line, which would, it is believed, lead him to the '''Polynya'''—a ''mare liberum'', or such, comparatively speaking—within its formidable borderings of the thick-ribbed ice.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|chapter=Summary of the Meeting|title=Polar Bears:{{nb...|Proceedings of the Seventh Working Meeting of the IUCN Polar Bear Specialist Group Held at the Artisk Institut, Copenhagen, Denmark, 30 January&nbsp;– 1 February 1979 and Proceedings of the Sixth Working Meeting of the IUCN Polar Bear Specialist Group Held at IUCN Headquarters, Switzerland, 7–10 December 1976}}|location=Gland, Switzerland|publisher=[[w:International Union for Conservation of Nature|International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]]|year=1980|section=paragraph 9|page=23|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=z784DCYBrZsC&pg=PA23|isbn=978-2-88032-206-9|passage=Dr. [[w:Ian Stirling (biologist)|[Ian] Stirling]] pointed out that colonies of nesting sea-birds were an indicator of permanent '''polynias''' and that the productivity studies in such '''polynias''' might prove interesting.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|chapter=Description of the Affected Environment|title=Proposed Diapir Field Lease Offering (June 1984): Final Environmental Impact Statement|series=Outer Continental Shelf EIS|seriesvolume=MMS 84-0009|location=[Anchorage, Ak.]|publisher=Minerals Management Service, Alaska Outer Continental Shelf Region, {{w|United States Department of the Interior}}|month=March|year=1984|section=section A.3 (Sea Ice)|page=III-23|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=hS4RAAAAYAAJ&pg=SA1-PA113|oclc=10565162|passage=Along the western Alaska coast between Point Hope and Point Barrow, there is often a band of open-water seaward of the landfast ice zone during winter and spring {{...}}. This opening is at times a well-defined lead and at other times a series of openings in the sea ice or '''polynyi'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|chapter=Environmental Consequences|title=Proposed Norton Basin Sale 100: Final Environmental Impact Statement|series=OCS EIS/ES; MMS 85-0085|location=[Anchorage, Ak.]|publisher=Minerals Management System, Alaska Outer Continental Shelf Region, {{w|United States Department of the Interior}}|month=December|year=1985|volume=I|section=section A.2(a) (Fate and Behavior of Spilled Oil)|page=IV-A-21|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvQkF_3_brkC&pg=RA10-PA21|oclc=1103309097|passage=To get into the water of a '''polynya''' earlier than breakup, oil would have to be spilled into a '''polynya''' or a '''polynya''' would have to form through the ice-entrapped spill; that is, break the ice in the middle of the frozen spill.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=George A. Knox|chapter=The Southern Ocean|title=Biology of the Southern Ocean|edition=2nd|series=Marine Biology Series|location=Boca Raton, Fla.|publisher={{w|CRC Press}}|year=2006|section=section 1.6 (Circulation Patterns and Water Masses)|page=11|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=lF_LBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA11|column=1|isbn=978-0-8493-3394-1|passage='''Polynas''' play an important role in heat transfer from the oceans to the atmosphere, ice production, the formation of dense shelf water, spring disintegration of sea ice, phytoplankton and zooplankton production, and the distribution of higher trophic animals such as cephalopods, fish, birds, seals, and cetaceans. Within '''polynas''', the oceanic heat loss may be 10–100 times above that of the ice-covered surface.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ola M. Johannessen [''et al.'']|chapter=Sea-ice Conditions in the Arctic and in the Northern Sea Route|title=Remote Sensing of Sea Ice in the Northern Sea Route: Studies and Applications|series=Springer–Praxis Books in Geophysical Sciences; Nansen Center’s Polar Series|seriesvolume=no. 4|location=Berlin; Heidelberg|publisher=[[w:Springer Science+Business Media|Springer-Verlag]]; Chichester, West Sussex: Published in association with Praxis Publishing|year=2007|section=section 2.2.3 (Landfast Ice and Polynyas of the Arctic Seas)|page=60|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=04a7ITII-H4C&pg=PA60|isbn=978-3-540-24448-6|passage=The appearance of flaw '''polynyas''' and of coastal '''polynyas''', in the absence of landfast ice, depends on the direction and duration of off-ice and offshore (i.e., from the shore) wind, and also on the orientation of the ice boundary relative to the wind direction. '''Polynyas''' present extensive areas of tens to hundreds of kilometers of open water or young ice up to 30 cm thick forming between landfast ice and drifting ice.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Jane George|title=‘We’ve had the biggest surprises and more questions are coming out.’: The secret life of snowy owls|url=https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/Weve_had_the_biggest_surprises_and_more_questions_are_coming_out/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229204314/https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/Weve_had_the_biggest_surprises_and_more_questions_are_coming_out/|archivedate=29 December 2018|newspaper={{w|Nunatsiaq News}}|date=20 June 2008|passage=Researchers now plan to compare their routes with satellite images and see whether the owls stayed around the '''polynas''', where snowy owls have been seen, picking off eiders swimming in the open water.}}

